                                                    <div class="et_pb_blurb_container">
                                                        <h4 class="et_pb_module_header"><span>Cyber Essentials Basic vs Cyber Essentials PLUS Explanation</span></h4>
                                                        <div class="et_pb_blurb_description"><p><span>Many organisations approach us for advice and guidance about whether to apply for Cyber Essentials or Cyber Essentials PLUS. Although the differences can appear confusing we work with you to access which of the two Schemes are most appropriate for your organisation.</span></p></div>
                                                    </div>
                                                </div>
                                            </div> <div class="et_pb_module et_pb_blurb et_pb_blurb_1 et_hover_enabled  et_pb_text_align_left  et_pb_blurb_position_left et_pb_bg_layout_light">
                                                <div class="et_pb_blurb_content">
                                                    <div class="et_pb_main_blurb_image"><span class="et_pb_image_wrap"><span class="et-waypoint et_pb_animation_off et-pb-icon">&#x3d;</span></span></div>
                                                    <div class="et_pb_blurb_container">
                                                        <h4 class="et_pb_module_header"><span>Cyber Essentials Basic vs Cyber Essentials PLUS Breakdown</span></h4>
                                                        <div class="et_pb_blurb_description"><p><span>The Cyber Essentials Scheme is effectively a UK recognised cyber security standard. The Scheme encapsulates a </span><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.cyberessentials.ncsc.gov.uk/requirements-for-it-infrastructure" target="_blank">set list of requirements</a><span> that your organisation can be assessed against. Basic Cyber Essentials and Cyber Essentials PLUS assessments are applied utilising the list of requirements and, therefore, are the same Scheme.</span></p></div>
                                                    </div>
                                                </div>
                                            </div>
                                        </div>
                                    </div> <div class="et_pb_row et_pb_row_5">
                                        <div class="et_pb_column et_pb_column_4_4 et_pb_column_8  et_pb_css_mix_blend_mode_passthrough et-last-child">
                                            <div class="et_pb_module et_pb_blurb et_pb_blurb_2 et_hover_enabled  et_pb_text_align_left  et_pb_blurb_position_left et_pb_bg_layout_light">
                                                <div class="et_pb_blurb_content">
                                                    <div class="et_pb_main_blurb_image"><span class="et_pb_image_wrap"><span class="et-waypoint et_pb_animation_off et-pb-icon">&#x3d;</span></span></div>
                                                    <div class="et_pb_blurb_container">
                                                        <h4 class="et_pb_module_header"><span>The differences between Basic Cyber Essentials and Cyber Essentials PLUS</span></h4>
                                                        <div class="et_pb_blurb_description"><p>Since the approach are the same for both levels, the difference is with how the assessments are undertaken by CSi and one of our Certification Bodies to<span> </span><strong>verify</strong> that your organisation meets, or exceeds, the requirements of the Scheme. </p>
                                                            <p>Basic Cyber Essentials is a self-certification process. The process is intuitive and involves providing answers to a questionnaire, supported with evidence, and the application is assessed by one of our certification bodies through our <a href="https://www.csi.team/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">online portal.</a></p>
                                                            <p>Cyber Essentials PLUS is a more intrusive and testing process as it includes a vulnerability scan of your organisations network. This entails one of our certification bodies visiting your organisation’s office(s) and undertake a Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) exercise that is in line with the Cyber Essentials requirements. Every certification body will have the same penetration testing although the costs may vary.</p></div>
                                                    </div>
                                                </div>
                                            </div> <div class="et_pb_module et_pb_blurb et_pb_blurb_3 et_hover_enabled  et_pb_text_align_left  et_pb_blurb_position_left et_pb_bg_layout_light">
                                                <div class="et_pb_blurb_content">
                                                    <div class="et_pb_main_blurb_image"><span class="et_pb_image_wrap"><span class="et-waypoint et_pb_animation_off et-pb-icon">&#x3d;</span></span></div>
                                                    <div class="et_pb_blurb_container">
                                                        <h4 class="et_pb_module_header"><span>Deciding on Basic Cyber Essentials Basic or Cyber Essentials PLUS</span></h4>
                                                        <div class="et_pb_blurb_description"><p>The selection of which level of Cyber Essentials depends on the business needs of your organisation. The following list includes some drivers but is not exclusive:</p>
                                                            <ul>
                                                                <li>Demonstrate a Responsible Business – providing confidence to your clients that your organisation’s data is handled securely</li>
                                                                <li>Business Continuity – Independent confirmation that the technical cyber security measures that your organisation has in place are adequate to reduce the possibility of a cyber security event</li>
                                                                <li>Business Winning – either certification under the Scheme is required to meet the requirements of a government contract/tender</li>
                                                                <li>IT Support/Managed Service Provider – if your organisation includes these as clients then they may well wish to attain certification under the Scheme for any or all of the above mention reasons</li>
                                                            </ul></div>
                                                    </div>
                                                </div>
                                            </div> <div class="et_pb_module et_pb_blurb et_pb_blurb_4 et_hover_enabled  et_pb_text_align_left  et_pb_blurb_position_left et_pb_bg_layout_light">
                                                <div class="et_pb_blurb_content">
                                                    <div class="et_pb_main_blurb_image"><span class="et_pb_image_wrap"><span class="et-waypoint et_pb_animation_off et-pb-icon">&#x3d;</span></span></div>
                                                    <div class="et_pb_blurb_container">
                                                        <h5 class="et_pb_module_header"><span>Cyber Essentials Basic vs Cyber Essentials PLUS vs ISO27001</span></h5>
                                                        <div class="et_pb_blurb_description"><p><strong><em></em></strong></p>
                                                            <p><strong><em>What is the Relationship Between ISO 27001 certification, Cyber Essentials/Cyber Essentials PLUS Certification?</em></strong></p>
                                                            <p>ISO 27001 (formally known as <em>ISO/IEC 27001:2005</em>) is a specification for an Information Security Management System (ISMS). An ISMS is a framework of policies, processes and procedures that includes all legal, physical and technical controls involved in an organisation’s information risk management processes. Properly undertaken ISO 27001 includes an assessment of the three pillars of information security – the physical environs, the personnel and the organisation’s network and associated assets.</p>
                                                            <p>ISO 27001 is a more granular certification process, whereas the Cyber Essentials Scheme confirms that the essential elements of your organisation’s network security are up to National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) standards. As previously mention the Cyber Essentials scheme is a UK only recognised Scheme. If your organisation operates in markets beyond the UK then CSi would recommend a CSi ‘enhanced’ ISO 27001 which includes the elements of the Cyber Essentials Scheme.</p></div>
                                                    </div>
                                                </div>
